free_txt: Institute of Nuclear Science, Grenoble

The deuterons scattered a water target were
detected in a high-resolution spectrometer of
energy-loss type.

The deuterons were identified by their time of
flight measured between a hodoscope composed of ten
scintillators, placed 2.9 m behind.
The energy resolution  dE of the detected deuterons
resulted essentially from energy loss straggling in the
water target, typically energy resolution was 520 keV
for 200 MeV deuterons through a 5.3 mm target, and 910
keV for 400 MeV deuterons through a 11.9 mm target.
Target consisted of a 4 cm diameter hole in a 3 or 10
mm thick slab of a aluminium placed perpendicular to
the incident beam. The ends of the hole were sealed by
50 mu-m thick foils of mylar. The target, placed at the
center of the vacuum reaction chamber, expanded so that
the effective thickness had to be measured by
comparison with a 2.5 or 5 mm thick mylar target. The
actual water thicknesses were 5.3 and 11.9 mm with a 5%
uncertainty.
